## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of practical CQRS with event-sourcing: building a read-model that stays consistent as events arrive.

## Key Concepts
- Read-model projection for CQRS
- Event ordering and idempotent application
- Tombstone/deletion semantics
- Handling out-of-order events via versioning and replay

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal projection function
function applyEvent(readModel, event) {
  const { type, id, version } = event;
  if (type === 'OrderCreated') {
    readModel[id] = { id, status: 'Created', total: 0, version };
  } else {
    const row = readModel[id];
    if (!row || row.version > version) return; // idempotent guard
    row.version = version;
    if (type === 'ItemAdded') row.total += event.price * event.quantity;
    if (type === 'ItemRemoved') row.total -= event.price * event.quantity;
    if (type === 'PaymentCompleted') row.status = 'Paid';
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle reprocessing after a schema change or migration?
- How would you expose consistency guarantees in presence of multi-tenant data isolation?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical cache invalidation and per-tenant isolation with Redis. It emphasizes correctness over theory and keeps memory footprints predictable.

## Key Concepts
- Cache-aside pattern with tenant keys
- TTL tuning and avoidance of stampedes
- Pub/Sub vs. central bus for invalidation

## Code Example
```javascript
const KEY = (tid, pid) => `tenant:${tid}:product:${pid}`
async function getWithCache(tid, pid, loadFromDb, cache, ttl=300){
  const k = KEY(tid, pid)
  let v = await cache.get(k)
  if (v) return JSON.parse(v)
  const row = await loadFromDb(tid, pid)
  await cache.set(k, JSON.stringify(row), ttl)
  return row
}
// on update
async function invalidate(tid, pid, pub, cache){
  await pub.publish(`tenant:${tid}:cache:product`, JSON.stringify({pid}))
  await cache.del(KEY(tid,pid))
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle cross-tenant eviction storms if many tenants update simultaneously?
- How would you monitor cache hit rate and TTL effectiveness in production?

## Why This Is Asked

This question tests practical, scalable cache invalidation across services, covering Redis pub/sub, versioned keys, and cross-tenant isolation.

## Key Concepts

- Cache-aside vs write-through
- Versioned keys: item:{id}:v and item:{id}
- Redis pub/sub for coordinated invalidation
- Stampede prevention: refresh locks and TTL tuning

## Code Example

```javascript
// Write path (pseudo)
function updateItem(id, value){
  const vKey = `item:${id}:v`;
  const valueKey = `item:${id}`;
  const newV = Date.now();
  redis.incr(vKey);
  redis.set(valueKey, value, 'EX', 60);
  redis.publish('invalidation', JSON.stringify({id, v:newV}));
}
```

```javascript
// Read path (pseudo)
async function readItem(id){
  const vKey = `item:${id}:v`;
  const valueKey = `item:${id}`;
  const currentV = await redis.get(vKey) || 0;
  let value = await cache.get(valueKey);
  if(!value){
     value = db.query(id);
     cache.set(valueKey, value, 60);
  }
  const cachedV = parseInt(await redis.get(vKey) || '0', 10);
  if(currentV > cachedV){
     value = db.query(id);
     cache.set(valueKey, value, 60);
     redis.set(vKey, currentV);
  }
  return value;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you tune TTLs for latency vs staleness across tenants?
- How would you rotate keys and migrate tenants without downtime?

